---
import MainLayout from "../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
---

<MainLayout title="Olle Rönn | Learning Log">
  <section class="hero learning-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Learning Log</p>

    <h1>Learning Log</h1>

    <p class="lead">
      This page summarizes what I have worked on, what I have learned and how my
      technical projects develop over time. It works as a short learning journal
      for my portfolio, GitHub projects and practical technical development.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Log</p>
      <h2>Latest sessions</h2>
      <p>
        Short summaries of recent work on my portfolio, Secure Homelab and other
        technical projects.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="log-list">

    <article class="log-entry current">
  <div class="log-date">
    <span>2026-05-16</span>
    <p>Session 7</p>
  </div>

  <div class="log-content">
    <h3>Completed Cloud Homelab v2 with monitoring and Azure logs</h3>

    <p>
      I continued and completed Cloud Homelab v2 as a portfolio-ready hybrid cloud
      project. The project now connects my local Secure Homelab v1 with an Azure
      deployment using FastAPI, Docker, GitHub Actions CI, Azure Container Registry
      and Azure Container Apps.
    </p>

    <p>
      I added monitoring by connecting my local Uptime Kuma instance to the Azure
      API health endpoint. The monitor checks the <code>/health</code> endpoint
      every 60 seconds and confirmed that the deployed API was reachable and healthy.
    </p>

    <p>
      I also verified the deployment through Azure Log Stream. The logs showed
      successful requests to endpoints such as <code>/health</code> and
      <code>/version</code>, confirming that the Azure Container App was receiving
      traffic and responding correctly.
    </p>

    <p>
      I finished the project documentation by adding monitoring documentation,
      Azure logs documentation, a final version 2 summary and a complete README.
      I also updated earlier documentation files so they matched the finished
      project status and removed exposed API key examples from the documentation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Learned:</strong> I gained practical experience with hybrid cloud
      monitoring, Azure Container Apps, Azure Log Stream, GitHub Actions CI,
      technical documentation, API security and safe handling of secrets in
      documentation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Result:</strong> Cloud Homelab v2 is complete as Version 2. It now
      includes a working Azure deployment, passing CI, Uptime Kuma monitoring,
      Azure log verification, screenshots and full documentation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Limitation:</strong> A planned v2.1 CI/CD deployment step was paused
      because the Azure for Students tenant did not allow the required app
      registration or service principal permissions for secure OIDC-based deployment.
      This was documented as a future improvement instead of using a less secure
      workaround with long-lived credentials.
    </p>
  </div>
</article>

   <article class="log-entry">
  <div class="log-date">
    <span>2026-05-15</span>
    <p>Session 6</p>
  </div>

  <div class="log-content">
    <h3>Built and deployed Cloud Homelab v2 to Azure</h3>

    <p>
      I continued my roadmap project Cloud Homelab v2 - Secure Hybrid Cloud
      Deployment. The goal of the project is to extend my local Secure Homelab v1
      into a cloud-based deployment using FastAPI, Docker, Azure, GitHub Actions
      and monitoring.
    </p>

    <p>
      I created a new GitHub repository, structured the project with folders for
      the application, tests, documentation, diagrams, screenshots and GitHub
      Actions workflows, and built a FastAPI application with root, health,
      version and protected API endpoints.
    </p>

    <p>
      I added environment-based configuration with APP_NAME, APP_VERSION, APP_ENV
      and API_KEY, and implemented simple API security where the protected
      endpoint requires an API key through the <code>x-api-key</code> header.
    </p>

    <p>
      I dockerized the application with a Dockerfile, docker-compose.yml and
      .dockerignore, tested the API locally in Docker and added automated pytest
      tests for the health, version and secure endpoints. GitHub Actions CI was
      configured to run the tests automatically on push to main, and the workflow
      completed successfully.
    </p>

    <p>
      I then deployed the application to Azure by creating a resource group,
      Azure Container Registry, Azure Container App and Container Apps Environment
      in North Europe. The Docker image was pushed to ACR and the application was
      deployed with ingress enabled on port 8000.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Learned:</strong> I gained practical experience with FastAPI,
      Docker, API security, environment variables, automated testing, GitHub
      Actions CI, Azure Container Registry, Azure Container Apps and cloud
      deployment troubleshooting.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Result:</strong> Cloud Homelab v2 now has a working Azure deployment,
      passing CI, documented local development, Dockerization, testing and Azure
      deployment, plus screenshots showing the running cloud application.
    </p>
  </div>
</article>

     <article class="log-entry">
        <div class="log-date">
          <span>2026-05-14</span>
          <p>Session 5</p>
        </div>

        <div class="log-content">
          <h3>Completed Secure Homelab version 1</h3>

          <p>
            I completed the first version of my Secure Homelab project. The final
            setup is a Linux-based server environment running Ubuntu Server inside
            VirtualBox, with secure SSH access, firewall rules, fail2ban, Docker
            and several internal services.
          </p>

          <p>
            I installed and verified Docker and Docker Compose, created a shared
            Docker network and configured Portainer, Uptime Kuma, Homepage and
            Nginx as internal Docker-based services. Uptime Kuma was configured
            to monitor the internal services through Docker container names.
          </p>

          <p>
            I also cleaned up the GitHub documentation, added architecture
            diagrams, organized screenshots and wrote a final version 1 summary.
            The documentation now covers the VM setup, networking, installation,
            security configuration, Docker services, lessons learned and the final
            project status.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Learned:</strong> I gained practical experience with Linux
            server administration, SSH hardening, UFW, fail2ban, Docker networking,
            service monitoring and technical documentation.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Result:</strong> Secure Homelab v1 is complete, documented and
            ready to be presented as a portfolio project.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="log-entry">
        <div class="log-date">
          <span>2026-05-12</span>
          <p>Session 4</p>
        </div>

        <div class="log-content">
          <h3>Started Secure Homelab with Ubuntu Server and SSH</h3>

          <p>
            I started my Secure Homelab project by creating a GitHub repository
            with a documentation structure and installing Ubuntu Server in a
            VirtualBox virtual machine.
          </p>

          <p>
            The server was configured with RAM, CPU, virtual disk, NAT networking,
            hostname and a local user. After installation, I updated the system,
            installed basic tools and checked the server networking information.
          </p>

          <p>
            I ran into an issue where SSH from Windows to the VM IP address timed
            out. By checking the SSH service status on the server, I could see
            that SSH itself was running and that the issue was caused by VirtualBox
            NAT. The solution was to configure port forwarding from Windows to the
            Ubuntu server.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Learned:</strong> I gained a better understanding of the
            difference between host and guest systems, how NAT works in VirtualBox,
            why port forwarding is needed for SSH and how to troubleshoot SSH with
            systemctl.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Result:</strong> The first checkpoint was completed. Ubuntu
            Server was installed, updated and reachable via SSH from Windows.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="log-entry">
        <div class="log-date">
          <span>2026-05-11</span>
          <p>Session 3</p>
        </div>

        <div class="log-content">
          <h3>Tested, deployed and published the portfolio</h3>

          <p>
            I performed the final checks of the portfolio, tested the pages in
            both desktop and mobile views and made sure that links, layout and
            content worked as intended.
          </p>

          <p>
            I also deployed the website with Vercel and connected the project to
            GitHub, so the site automatically updates when new changes are pushed
            to the main branch.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Learned:</strong> I gained a better understanding of how GitHub,
            Vercel, the build process and deployment work together in a real web
            project.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Result:</strong> The first version of the portfolio went live
            and can now be updated continuously with new projects, improvements
            and learning logs.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="log-entry">
        <div class="log-date">
          <span>2026-05-11</span>
          <p>Session 2</p>
        </div>

        <div class="log-content">
          <h3>Refined the portfolio design and content</h3>

          <p>
            I continued improving the portfolio to make it more complete and
            professional. The focus was on improving the overall feel, making the
            design more minimal and consistent, and making the pages work better
            together.
          </p>

          <p>
            I updated several pages, including the homepage, CV, projects,
            homelab and contact pages. The pages received clearer structure,
            better content and a more consistent presentation of my profile,
            projects and technical direction.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Learned:</strong> I gained a better understanding of how
            content, layout, components and CSS work together in Astro to create
            a more professional and coherent portfolio.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Result:</strong> The portfolio received a clearer design,
            more refined content and a more consistent structure between pages.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="log-entry">
        <div class="log-date">
          <span>2026-05-08</span>
          <p>Session 1</p>
        </div>

        <div class="log-content">
          <h3>Started the portfolio project with Astro</h3>

          <p>
            I set up the foundation for the portfolio website with Astro and
            created the main pages: homepage, CV, projects, learning log, homelab
            and contact.
          </p>

          <p>
            I also started building a shared structure with layout, navigation,
            footer and reusable parts, so the site can grow with more projects
            and documentation over time.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Learned:</strong> I gained a clearer understanding of how
            Astro projects are structured with pages, layouts, components and
            HTML-like structure in `.astro` files.
          </p>

          <p>
            <strong>Result:</strong> The foundation for the portfolio was in
            place and the project could continue with improved design and content.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="learning-focus">
  <div>
    <p class="eyebrow">Current focus</p>
    <h2>Roadmap continuation</h2>
    <p>
      Secure Homelab v1 and Cloud Homelab v2 are now complete and documented.
      The next roadmap steps are focused on Secure NAS / Home Cloud, monitoring,
      logging and future CI/CD improvements when the required Azure permissions
      are available.
    </p>
  </div>

  <a class="focus-card" href="/projects">
    <span class="tag">Project overview</span>
    <h3>View projects</h3>
    <p>
      Go to the projects page to see completed projects, planned roadmap areas,
      GitHub links, project status and the technologies used.
    </p>
  </a>
</section>
</MainLayout>

<style>
  .learning-hero h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 5.2vw, 4.2rem);
  }

  .log-list {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }

  .log-entry {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 180px 1fr;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    padding: 1.35rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035), rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.015)),
      var(--surface);
    transition:
      transform 160ms ease,
      border-color 160ms ease,
      background 160ms ease;
  }

  .log-entry:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    border-color: var(--border-hover);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.045), rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.02)),
      var(--surface-soft);
  }

  .log-entry.current {
    border-color: var(--border-hover);
  }

  .log-date span {
    display: block;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-weight: 850;
    margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
  }

  .log-date p {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .log-content h3 {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .log-content p {
    max-width: 780px;
  }

  .learning-focus {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.25fr) minmax(280px, 0.8fr);
    gap: 1rem;
    align-items: stretch;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.045), rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.018)),
      var(--surface);
    transition:
      transform 160ms ease,
      border-color 160ms ease,
      background 160ms ease;
  }

  .learning-focus:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    border-color: var(--border-hover);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.045), rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.02)),
      var(--surface-soft);
  }

  .learning-focus p {
    max-width: 720px;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .focus-card {
    display: block;
    padding: 1.2rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035), rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.015)),
      var(--surface);
    text-decoration: none;
    color: inherit;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition:
      transform 160ms ease,
      border-color 160ms ease,
      background 160ms ease;
  }

  .focus-card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    border-color: var(--border-hover);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.045), rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.02)),
      var(--surface-soft);
  }

  .focus-card h3 {
    transition: color 160ms ease;
  }

  .focus-card:hover h3 {
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .focus-card p {
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  @media (max-width: 860px) {
    .log-entry {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 0.75rem;
    }

    .learning-focus {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
